My thoughts on prayer in school: I don't approve of it. When I was 7 years old, I was visiting the US, and went to school there for some months. Every day, I was required to stand up and sing the national anthem of, and swear allegience to the flag of, a country which was not my own.<br>
<br>
Back in Australia, in a government school, we had some kind of &quot;religious education&quot; which all but one of the kids in my year attended. There may have been separate classes for Catholics and Protestants, I'm not sure. The one child who spent that time of the day in the library was Buddhist, and did not attend at his parent's request, but I'm sure he felt quite isolated by the process. My family was not religious, and that's probably the same for many others, but there was a pressure to attend anyway. Small children are easily influenced like that. I know I felt uncomfortable about both situations, but wasn't prepared to do anything about it. I'm sure that technically it wasn't the case, but in reality, the prayers and bible of a faith I did not believe in were being forced apon me. Children in schools should be allowed to pray in their chosen way, but not have others prayers forced apon them. I'm not sure how to do this fairly, but reading prayers over the school intercom would not be the way to do it.<br>
<br>
I attended a private high school run by the Uniting Church. I have no problems with the school chaplain, or mandated prayers, there. I actually found the chaplain to be quite open-minded and reasonable in his views on other religions. There was greek orthodox iconography and a jewish menorah in the chapel. I was kinda miffed about the detention I received for &quot;incessant chatter during worship&quot;. As I recall it I was talking whilst they were reading out the sports results in school assembly... then again, sport was almost a form of worship at that school <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Religion in government? I don't think it belongs there (in most countries). I don't have a problem with individual parlimentarians saying their prayers as they wish. I'm a little more dubious, but still can see reason in them having a chaplain - but that should probably be accounted to their expenses, rather than directly state funded. A parlimentary chapel? Umm.. unless you're very careful that can get to be discriminatory. And politicians need to be very careful making statements that praise, thank, or otherwise refer to God or religion. Even though they may be personal beliefs, you don't want to get personal beliefs mixed up with public or official opinions. It's my opinion that in taking up political positions, you assume certain responsibilities, and one of those is not to let your personal opinions cloud your public stance and image. Fred Nile is an Australian politician who runs a right-wing christian party. Much as I dislike his stance on many issues, I'll allow that it <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> should</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> be based on religious issues, since that's his election platform. The prime minister, John Howard, is also a right-wing christian, but I don't think it's appropriate for him to make decisions based on religion. <p>----------------------------------<br>
[59 Troubadour]
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=78662">Maeri</a>
&lt;Anlah'Shok&gt;</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/urheaton.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Rheaton</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 194<br> <font color=#E9D756>(5/30/02 5:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=302.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Simple, Clear and Poweful</span><hr size=1> <br>
Although some people do wear their religion like a hat, isn’t religion something that you take and have with you 24/7? There are two very familiar signs we see today...one is No Smoking and the other is No Concealed Weapons... What’s next, an R in a circle with a slash through it?<br>
<br>
In America, we elect our representatives based upon how well we think they will represent us. If we are conservative Christian, then we vote for thus...Likewise if one is liberal atheist...That’s the beauty of a democracy. We get to vote for those whom (we hope) will have our best interest in mind and heart, but all the while maintaining our rights.<br>
<br>
An atheist may very well think that a prayer before a meeting is uncalled for, while a Christian may think that not praying before a meeting is wrong. The solution is, according to constitutional rights, is not to cease all religion based upon some personal technicality, but to be able to freely exercise your personal beliefs. Your not ramming atheism down my throat by not praying before a meeting any more then a Christian does by praying before a meeting.<br>
<br>
There has to be 'morals' in law. There are many 'moral' laws that we can all agree with already that no one would want to change. Can anyone think of a few? These are more then &quot;common sense&quot; laws..Why is murder and stealing a crime? Why is bestiality and statutory rape a crime? If we dig deep enough into these laws I think we will find morality.<br>
<br>
As far as prayer over the schools PA system, I am not for it. The reason is that I do not want my children to be 'pressured' into praying to a god that I do not approve of. Yes, right now Christianity is the majority, but what if a different religion comes along some day and replaces it? I do not want my children praying to some bogus, false god or even participating in and attending a school that promotes what I may consider a bogus or false religion. However, at the same time I do not want my children to have to leave their religion and beliefs at the door. A truly free person can take their beliefs with them anywhere they go..be it a school, Wal-Mart, the senate or at home. A liberal dissection of the constitution based upon a Supreme Court ruling that all but removes our rights to religion in an state sponsored or state funded facility should be a slap in the face to us all! Even those who do not like to hear God's word or do not like 'bible thumpers' pushing their beliefs in our faces should be proud that that person has a right to and is exercising their constitutional rights.<br>
<br>
I think all will agree that there is much garbage on TV nowadays. There is alot of crap we do not want our children to watch and see. How do we fix it? We turn off the TV. Boycott it if you will by not watching it, but to demand that TVs not be sold or that an artist may not exercise their right to self-expression cause we live in the 'sticks' and can only get one station is unconstitutional. Right? I know some will say there is a difference between having control of a TV set and being approached in public where you cant just 'turn off the Christian' and there is some truth to that. ..But the issue isn’t personal 'space' or personal censorship as much as it is about inalienable constitutional rights.<br>
<br>
<br>
